.graphics by eric haines' b'' b"there's a more concise reference also:" b'' b'"theoretical foundations for computer graphics and cad", ed. r.a.e.earnshaw,' b'nato as, vol. f-40., pp. printed by springer-verlag, b'' b'it contains code for a small, but fundamentally complete ray-tracer.' b'' b'b. z-buffer (depth-buffer)' b'--------------------------' b'' b'a good reference is:' b'' b'_procedural elements for computer graphics_, david f. rogers,' b'mcgraw-hill, new york, pages and b'' b'c. others:' b'----------' b'???' b'[ more info is needed nfotis b'' b'========================================================================' b'' b'15. where can i find the geometric data for the:' b'================================================' b'' b'a. teapot b'-----------' b'' b'"displays on display" column of ieee cg&a jan has the whole' b"story about origin of the martin newell's teapot. the article also has" b'the bezier patch model and a pascal program to display the wireframe' b'model of the teapot.' b'' b'ieee cg&a sep in jim blinn\'s column "jim blinn\'s corner" describes' b'an another way to model the teapot; bezier curves with rotations for' b'example are used.' b'' b"the off and spd packages have these objects, so you're advised to get" b'them to avoid typing the data yourself. the off data is triangles at' b'a specific resolution (around 8x8[x4 triangles] meshing per patch).' b'the spd package provides the spline patch descriptions and performs a' b'tessellation at any specified resolution.' b'' b'b. space shuttle b'------------------' b'' b"datafiles. here's a summary (from his sci.space list):" b'' b'model1:' b'a modified version of the newsgroup model (model2)' b'' b'406 vertices useful, i.e. referred to in the polygon descriptions.)' b'389 polygons 3-vertex, 4-vertex, 5-vertex, 6-vertex).' b'payload doors non-existent.' b'units: unknown.' b'' b'said there is no proprietary information associated with it.' b'' b'model2:' b'the newsgroup model, in off format. you can find it in' b'' b'gondwana.ecr.mu.oz.au file pub/off/objects/shuttle.geo' b'hanauma.stanford.edu /pub/graphics/comp.graphics/objects/shuttle.data' b'' b'model3:' b"the triangles' model." b'' b'this model is stored in several files, each defining portions of the model.' b'' b"not mention any restriction on the model's distribution." b'' b'model4:' b'the nasa model.' b'' b'the file starts off with a header line containing three real numbers,' b'defining the offsets used by lockheed in their simulations:' b'' b'<x offset <y offset <z offset' b'' b'from then on, the file consists of a sequence of polygon descriptions' b'' b'3473 vertices.' b'2748 polygons 3-vertex, 4-vertex, 5-vertex, 6-vertex,' b'10 7-vertex, 8-vertex, 12-vertex, 13-vertex, 15-vertex,' b'17 16-vertex, 17-vertex, 18-vertex, 19-vertex, 24-vertex).' b'payload doors closed.' b'units: inches.' b'' b'proprietary info: unknown' b'' b'model5:' b'the old shuttle model.' b'' b'the file consists of a sequence of polygon descriptions.' b'' b'104 vertices.' b'452 polygons 3-vertex, 4-vertex).' b'payload doors open.' b'units: meters.' b'' b'we have been using this model at star labs, stanford university, for' b'' b'========================================================================' b'' b'16. image annotation software' b'=============================' b'' b'a. touchup runs in sunview and is pretty good. it reads in' b"rasterfiles, but even if your image isn't normally stored" b'in rasterfile format you could use screendump to make it a' b'rasterfile.' b'' b"b. idraw (part of stanford's interviews distribution) can handle some" b"image formats in addition to being a macdraw like tool. i'm not" b'sure exactly what they are.' b"you can ftp the idraw's binary from interviews.stanford.edu." b'' b'c. tgif is another macdraw like tool that can handle x11 bitmap (xbm)' b'and x11 pixmap (xpm) formats. if the image you have is in formats' b'other than xbm or xpm, you can get the pbmplus toolkit to convert' b'things like gif or even some macintosh formats to xpm.' b"tgif's sources are available in the pub directory on cs.ucla.edu" b'(version of tgif at patchlevel plus patch8 and patch9)' b'' b'd. use the editimage facility of khoros (see below).' b'this is just one utility in the overall system- you can essentially do all' b'your image processing and macdraw-type graphics using this package.' b'' b'e. you might be able to get by with pbmplus. pbmtext gives you text output' b'bitmaps which can be overlaid on top of your image.' b'' b"f. 'ice' requires sun hardware running openwindows 3.it's a postscript-based" b"graphical editor,and it's available for anonymous ftp from internet host" b'eo.soest.hawaii.edu requires sun c++ and' b'two other locally developed packages, the lxt library (an xlib-based' b'toolkit) and a small c++ class library. all files (pub/ice.tar.z,' b'pub/lxt.tar.z and pub/ldgoc++.tar.z) are available in compressed' b'tar format. pub/ice.tar.z contains a readme that gives installation' b'instructions, as well as an extensive man page (ice.1).' b'a statically-linked compressed executable pub/ice-sun4.z for' b'sparc systems is also available for ftp.' b'' b'all software is the property of columbia university and may not' b'be redistributed without permission.' b'' b"ice means image composition environment and it's an imaging tool that" b'allows raster images to be combined with a wide variety of' b'postscript annotations in wysiwyg fashion via x11 imaging' b'routines and news postscript rasterizing.' b'' b'g. use imagemagick to annotate an image from your x server. pick the' b'position of your text with the cursor and choose your font and pen' b'color from a pull-down menu. imagemagick can read and write many' b'of the more popular image formats. imagemagick is available as' b'export.lcs.mit.edu: contrib/imagemagick.tar.z or at your nearest' b'x11 archive.' b'' b'========================================================================' b'' b'17. scientific visualization stuff' b'==================================' b'' b'x data slice (xds)' b'-------------------' b'bundled with the x11 distribution from mit,' b'in the contrib directory. available at ftp.ncsa.uiuc.edu b'(either as a source or binaries for various platforms).' b'' b'national center for supercomputing applications (ncsa) tool suite' b'-----------------------------------------------------------------' b'' b'platforms: unix workstations (dec, ibm, sgi, sun)' b'apple macintosh' b'cray supercomputers' b'' b'availability: now available. source code in the public domain.' b'ftp from ftp.ncsa.uiuc.edu.' b'' b'contact: national center for supercomputing applications' b'computing applications building' b'605 e. springfield ave.' b'champaign, il b'' b'cost: free (zero dollars).' b'' b'the suite includes tools for 2d image and 3d scene analysis and visualization.' b'the code is actively maintained and updated.' b'' b'spyglass' b'--------' b'they sell commercial versions of the ncsa tools. examples are:' b'' b'spyglass dicer (3d volumetric data analysis package)' b'platform: mac' b'' b'spyglass transform (2d data analysis package)' b'platforms: mac, sgi, sun, dec, hp, ibm' b'' b'contact:' b'spyglass, inc.' b'p.o. box b'champaign, il b'(217) b'' b'khoros patch b'------------------' b'available via anonymous ftp at pprg.eece.unm.edu b'cd to /pub/khoros to see what is available. it is huge mb), but good.' b'needs unix and x11r4. freely copied (not pd), complete with sources' b'and docs. very extensive and at its heart is visual programming.' b'khoros components include a visual programming language, code' b'generators for extending the visual language and adding new application' b'packages to the system, an interactive user interface editor, an' b'interactive image display package, an extensive library of image and' b'signal processing routines, and 2d/3d plotting packages.' b'' b'see comp.soft-sys.khoros on usenet and the relative faq for more info....' b'' b'contact:' b'' b'the khoros group' b'room eece dept.' b'university of new mexico' b'albuquerque, nm b'' b'' b'' b'macphase' b'--------' b'analysis visualization application for the macintosh.' b'operates on 1d and 2d data arrays. import/export several different file' b'formats. several different plotting options such as gray scale,' b'color raster, 3d wire frame, 3d surface, contour, vector, line, and' b'combinations. ffts, filtering, and other math functions, color look up' b'editor, array calculator, etc. shareware, available via anonymous ftp from' b'sumex-aim.stanford.edu in the info-mac/app directory.' b'' b'' b'iris explorer' b'-------------' b"it's an application creation system developed by silicon" b'graphics that provides visualisation and analysis functionality for' b'computational scientists, engineers and other scientists. the explorer' b'gui allows users to build custom applications without having to write' b'any, or a minimal amount of, traditonal code. also, existing code can' b'be easily integrated into the explorer environment. explorer currently' b'is available now on sgi and cray machines, but will become available on' b'other platforms in time. bundled with every new sgi machine, as far as' b'i know]' b'' b'see comp.graphics.explorer or comp.sys.sgi for discussion of the package.' b'' b'there are also two ftp servers for related stuff, modules etc.:' b'' b'ftp.epcc.ed.ac.uk b'swedishchef.lerc.nasa.gov mirror of the uk site' b'' b'ape' b'---' b"back in the 'old good days', you could get ape for nearly free." b'now has gone commercial and the following vendor supplies it:' b'' b'taravisual corporation' b'929 harrison avenue' b'columbus, ohio b'tel: and b'fax: b'' b'cost:' b'$895 (plus tax); runtime version with a site-license for a single user' b'(at a time), no limit on the number of machines in a cluster.' b'$895 includes support/maintenance and upgrades.' b'source code more. additional user licenses b'' b'the name of the package has become ape iii (tm).' b'khoros